data.title: Johnny Rotten's punk star stepdaughter dies of 'serious illness' aged 48
data.meta_description: Ari Up - whose real name was Arianna Forster - was a member of the all-girl punk-reggae act The Slits, who reformed occasionally to tour.
data.text:
Former Sex Pistols star John Lydon was today mourning the death of his stepdaughter Ari Up, herself a punk star.

Up - whose real name was Arianna Forster - was a member of the all-girl punk-reggae act The Slits, who re-formed occasionally to tour.

She died yesterday from a 'serious illness', and the death was announced on Lydon's website.

Tragic: Arianna Forster, stepdaughter of John Lydon, has died at the age of 48 of a 'serious illness'

While the details of how Up died have not been released, the Guardian is reporting it was cancer.

Up, 48, formed the band in 1976 with Paloma Romero - better known as Palmolive - Tessa Pollitt and Viv Albertine.

They were part of a music scene which was at the centre of the punk explosion and were most famously known for tracks such as Typical Girls and their cover of Heard It Through The Grapevine.

Lydon, better known as Johnny Rotten, is married to Up's mother Nora Forster - a German heiress whose father was a publisher of Germany's Der Spiegel magazine.

The Sex Pistol met Forster in 1976 during his time as lead singer of the band and they wed a year later.

Announcing the death on Johnlydon.com, a statement reads: 'John and Nora have asked us to let everyone know that Nora's daughter Arianna (aka Ari-Up) died today (Wednesday, October 20th) after a serious illness. She will be sadly missed.'

Rock star: Arianna (far right) with former band The Slits in the early 1980s

Up's manager Jeff Jacquin paid tribute to the singer on The Slits' MySpace page, saying: 'She influenced generations of women and created some of the most memorable music of our time, but Ari's true magic was how she affected people on the street, face to face, every day.

'She ate life up and spit it out.'

The cover of The Slits debut album, Cut - in which Up and her bandmates were photographed topless and smeared with mud - became an enduring punk image.

Arianna RIP: Lydon posted this message on his official website yesterday

The album briefly reached No.30 in the album charts in 1979.

Dreadlocked Up, who was born in Munich, was just 14 when she originally formed the group.

With her wild costumes and hair, she was the most flamboyant member of the band - her style reflecting her love of Caribbean culture.

Going solo: Ari Up performed with her backing group the True Warriors in Camden, North London in 2006

Wild and free: Ari's hair takes on a life of its own in this picture from 1975

When The Slits split up in 1981, she divided her time between Brooklyn, New York and Kingston, Jamaica, where she raised her three sons - twins Pablo and Pedro, and Wilton - as a single mother.

She continued to make music - first with the New Age Steppers, featuring a young Neneh Cherry, and more recently toured the UK as Ari Up and the True Warriors.

Her first solo album Dread More Dan Dead was released in 2005.

Up also reunited with former Slits bass player Pollitt in 2006 and released the album, Revenge Of The Killer Slits.
